## Identifying Indicators in Timeline Explorer

Load the parsed `$MFT` CSV into Timeline Explorer by dragging and dropping the file into the application. Search for the target file by name or extension.

Three indicators point to timestomping.

---

# Findings

## Finding 5.1 – Timestamp Mismatch (SI < FN)

Every NTFS file contains two timestamp records:

- **$STANDARD_INFORMATION (0x10)** – User-visible timestamps that Windows displays and which user-level processes can modify.
- **$FILE_NAME (0x30)** – Kernel-maintained timestamps that cannot be easily modified by attackers.

When the user-visible timestamp (0x10) is earlier than the kernel-maintained timestamp (0x30), MFTECmd flags the file as **SI < FN**.

This backward time gap is the primary forensic indicator of a file that has been timestomped into the past.

> **Note:** This technique will not detect the uncommon situation where timestamps are manipulated into the future, although future-dated files generally stand out during timeline analysis.

